To comply with the latest ISD AppSec requirements, we have enabled End-to-End Application Payload Encryption on the backend.
All APIs that send sensitive data via a JSON Body (POST/PUT requests) must now be encrypted using AES-256-GCM. The backend has been configured to automatically decrypt these payloads invisibly, so no API contracts or JSON shapes have changed. Here is exactly how to implement this in the React/Vite application.
Step 1: Capture the Session Key on Login
When the user successfully logs in, the backend /login API will now return a new field called sessionKey (A Base64 encoded 256-bit AES key).
You must store this key in your Redux store or React Context alongside the JWT.



// Example Response from /login API
{
  "accessToken": "eyJhbGciOi...",
  "refreshToken": "d7a8f9...",
  "sessionKey": "v/Xb9Y..."  <-- STORE THIS IN STATE
}



Note: If the JWT expires and you call the /refresh-token API, the backend will return this sessionKey again. Make sure you update it in your state!)
Step 2: Create the Encryption Utility
Create a new utility file in your frontend (e.g., src/utils/cryptoUtil.js). This uses the native, hardware-accelerated Web Crypto API to perform AES-GCM encryption.






// src/utils/cryptoUtil.js

/**
 * Encrypts a JSON payload using AES-256-GCM.
 * @param {Object} payload - The JSON body to encrypt.
 * @param {string} base64Key - The sessionKey received during login.
 * @returns {Promise<string>} - Returns "Base64(IV):Base64(Ciphertext)"
 */
export async function encryptPayload(payload, base64Key) {
    if (!base64Key) throw new Error("No session key found");

    // 1. Convert JSON payload to bytes
    const encoder = new TextEncoder();
    const data = encoder.encode(JSON.stringify(payload));

    // 2. Decode the Base64 Session Key to bytes
    const keyBytes = Uint8Array.from(atob(base64Key), c => c.charCodeAt(0));

    // 3. Import the key into the Web Crypto API
    const cryptoKey = await window.crypto.subtle.importKey(
        "raw",
        keyBytes,
        { name: "AES-GCM" },
        false,
        ["encrypt"]
    );

    // 4. Generate a random 12-byte Initialization Vector (IV)
    const iv = window.crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(12));

    // 5. Encrypt the data
    const encryptedBuffer = await window.crypto.subtle.encrypt(
        { name: "AES-GCM", iv: iv },
        cryptoKey,
        data
    );

    // 6. Convert IV and Ciphertext to Base64
    const base64Iv = btoa(String.fromCharCode(...iv));
    const base64CipherText = btoa(String.fromCharCode(...new Uint8Array(encryptedBuffer)));

    // 7. Return in the exact format the backend expects
    return `${base64Iv}:${base64CipherText}`;
}






Step 3: Update your Axios Interceptor
You do not need to rewrite your API calls! You simply need to update your existing Axios request interceptor.
If it's a POST/PUT request with JSON data, the interceptor will intercept it, encrypt it, and add the X-Encrypted-Payload header.







// src/api/axiosSetup.js
import axios from 'axios';
import { encryptPayload } from '../utils/cryptoUtil';

const apiClient = axios.create({
    baseURL: 'https://fincore-uat.sbi/api',
});

// Request Interceptor
apiClient.interceptors.request.use(async (config) => {
    
    // 1. Add JWT Token (You probably already have this)
    const token = localStorage.getItem('accessToken');
    if (token) {
        config.headers.Authorization = `Bearer ${token}`;
    }

    // 2. APPLY PAYLOAD ENCRYPTION
    // Only encrypt if it's a POST/PUT/PATCH request AND has a JSON body
    if (['post', 'put', 'patch'].includes(config.method.toLowerCase()) && config.data) {
        
        // Skip encryption for FormData (like File Uploads)
        if (!(config.data instanceof FormData)) {
            
            // Get the AES Key from your Redux store / Context / LocalStorage
            const sessionKey = getSessionKeyFromState(); 
            
            if (sessionKey) {
                try {
                    // Encrypt the JSON body
                    const encryptedString = await encryptPayload(config.data, sessionKey);
                    
                    // Replace the original JSON with the encrypted string
                    config.data = encryptedString;
                    
                    // Add the Header so the Backend knows it needs to decrypt
                    config.headers['X-Encrypted-Payload'] = 'true';
                    // We must send it as plain text because it's no longer a JSON object
                    config.headers['Content-Type'] = 'text/plain'; 
                    
                } catch (error) {
                    console.error("Payload encryption failed:", error);
                    return Promise.reject(error);
                }
            }
        }
    }

    return config;
});

export default apiClient;

















Summary for Frontend:
1.	Login: Grab the sessionKey from the /login response.
2.	APIs: You don't need to change how you call APIs in your components. apiClient.post('/my-requests', { amount: 500 }) works exactly the same.
3.	The Magic: The Axios interceptor automatically turns { amount: 500 } into Base64(IV):Base64(Ciphertext) right before it hits the network!
